    "# 32. What are kernels in SVM? Can you list some popular SVM kernels."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "b47b9cba",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "What are Kernels in SVM?\n",
    "\n",
    "In a Support Vector Machine, a kernel is a function that lets you transform data into a higher-dimensional space without explicitly computing that transformation.\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 This is called the kernel trick.\n",
    "\n",
    "🎯 Why do we need kernels?\n",
    "Real-world data is often not linearly separable\n",
    "Kernels help SVM:\n",
    "Convert non-linear data → linearly separable\n",
    "Find an optimal hyperplane\n",
    "🧠 Intuition\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Instead of:\n",
    "\n",
    "Transforming data manually into high dimensions (expensive)\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Kernel does:\n",
    "\n",
    "Compute similarity directly in high-dimensional space\n",
    "📌 Mathematical Idea\n",
    "\n",
    "K(x,x\n",
    "′\n",
    ")=ϕ(x)⋅ϕ(x\n",
    "′\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "ϕ(x): transformation function\n",
    "Kernel computes dot product in transformed space\n",
    "✅ Popular SVM Kernels\n",
    "🔹 1. Linear Kernel\n",
    "\n",
    "K(x,x\n",
    "′\n",
    ")=x⋅x\n",
    "′\n",
    "\n",
    "✔️ Use when data is linearly separable\n",
    "✔️ Fast and simple\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 2. Polynomial Kernel\n",
    "\n",
    "K(x,x\n",
    "′\n",
    ")=(x⋅x\n",
    "′\n",
    "+c)\n",
    "d\n",
    "\n",
    "✔️ Captures feature interactions\n",
    "✔️ Useful for moderately complex data\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 3. RBF Kernel (Gaussian) — Most Popular\n",
    "\n",
    "K(x,x\n",
    "′\n",
    ")=exp(−γ∥x−x\n",
    "′\n",
    "∥\n",
    "2\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "✔️ Handles non-linear relationships\n",
    "✔️ Works well in most real-world cases\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 4. Sigmoid Kernel\n",
    "\n",
    "K(x,x\n",
    "′\n",
    ")=tanh(αx⋅x\n",
    "′\n",
    "+c)\n",
    "\n",
    "✔️ Similar to neural networks\n",
    "⚠️ Less commonly used\n",
    "\n",
    "🎯 When to Use Which?\n",
    "Kernel\tUse Case\n",
    "Linear\tHigh-dimensional data (text, NLP)\n",
    "Polynomial\tFeature interactions\n",
    "RBF\tDefault choice (most cases)\n",
    "Sigmoid\tRare / experimental\n",
    "🎯 Interview-Ready Answer (Short)**\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 “Kernels in SVM are functions that enable the model to handle non-linear data by implicitly mapping it into higher-dimensional space using the kernel trick. Common kernels include linear, polynomial, RBF, and sigmoid, with RBF being the most widely used.”\n",
    "\n",
    "🔥 Pro Tips (Must Say)\n",
    "👉 “RBF kernel is the default choice when data is non-linear.”\n",
    "👉 “Linear kernel works well for high-dimensional sparse data like text.”"
   ]
